  <annotation>Jens's next ballad, classified as a sk&#xE6;mtevise or joking ballad, is a clear satire on the romantic ballads that were quite popular at the time. It does not appear in DgF. The use of formula known from other ballads (saddling the gray steed for example), along with the insect protagonists, combine to make a song that most audiences would have recognized as satire.

     Tang Kristensen makes some slight changes in the published version, interpolating several lines, likely in an attempt to make the structure of the ballad more regular or to make the variant "more complete."</annotation>
  <danish_manuscript>Bramsen sadler sin Hoppe graa
     Trom tredeli trom tradila
s. ri'r han til den Flues Gaard,
     Trom tredeli trom tradila
Da h. kom hen til den Flues Gaard
da stod den Flue og reded sit Haar.
Og h&#xF8;r du flue vil du mig forstaa
skal vi to i &#xC6;gteskab indgaa.
---
Men Fluen gj&#xF8;rer af Bramsen Nar
naar jeg [naar] kan sidde paa min Frues Fad
saa maa [jeg] du sidde paa Hestens Bag.
Bramsen tog Fluen ved sit Vingeben
s. smed h. hende i Rendstenen ned
---
Den Flu hun rejser sig og rester sig
Aa fy for skam s. beskidder du mig
----
Og naar skal s. vores Bryllup staa
Ja [f&#xF8;rst] sidst om Sommeren og f&#xF8;rst om H&#xF8;st
s. er al Fluer og Bramser flest
---
Det blev [stor] gl&#xE6;de og den var stor
Det blev stor Gl&#xE6;de over al den Gaard
     udi den hele Sommer
Ja Bramsen f&#xE6;st og Fluen Brud
     di to &#xE6;dlige Blommer
</danish_manuscript>
  <english_manuscript>The horsefly saddles his gray steed
-Trom tredeli, trom tradeli-
then he rides off to the fly&#x2019;s farm
-Trom tredeli, trom tradeli-

When he got to the fly&#x2019;s farm
the fly stood there combing its hair

&#x201C;And listen, fly, will you listen to me
and should you and I get married?&#x201D;

But the fly makes fun of the horsefly

&#x201C;While I can sit on my mistress&#x2019;s platter,
you have to sit on the horse&#x2019;s behind

The horsefly took the fly by her wingbone
and he threw her down onto the cobblestone

That fly gets up and shakes herself off:
&#x201C;Oh, for shame&#x2019;s sake, you&#x2019;ve dirtied me!&#x201D;

 &#x201C;So when should our wedding be?&#x201D;

--Yes, at the end of the summer and at the beginning of autumn,
that&#x2019;s when all the flies and horseflies are most plentiful&#x201D;

There was happiness, and it was big
There was great happiness in the whole farm
-During the whole summer-
Yes the horsefly arranged to have the fly as his bride
-Those two noble plums
</english_manuscript>
  <danish_publication>1.   Bramsen sadler sin hoppe gr&#xE5;,
-  Trom tredeli, trom tradeli. &#x2014; 
s&#xE5; rier han hen til den flues g&#xE5;rd. 
Trom tredeli, trom tradeli.

3. "Og h&#xF8;r du, flue, vil du mig forst&#xE5;, 
skal vi to i &#xE6;gteskab indg&#xE5;?"

4. Men fluen gj&#xF8;rer af bremsen nar, 
[for hun jo meget villere var].

5. "N&#xE5;r jeg kan sidde p&#xE5; min frues fad, 
s&#xE5; m&#xE5; du sidde p&#xE5; hestens bag.

6.  Bramsen tog fluen ved sit vingeben, 
s&#xE5; smed han hende i rend'stenen ned.

7. Den flu' hun rejser sig og rester sig: 
"&#xC5;, fy for skam, s&#xE5; beskidder du mig!"

8. [Den flu' hun klynked', og halvt hun gr&#xE5;d:] 
"Og n&#xE5;r s&#xE5; skal vores bryllup st&#xE5;?"

9. &#x2014; "Ja, sidst om sommeren og f&#xF8;rst om h&#xF6;st, 
s&#xE5; er all' fluer og bramser flest".

10.  Der blev gl&#xE6;de, og den var stor,
&#x2014; Udi den hele sommer. &#x2014;
[den brams' han f&#xE6;st' s&#xE5; v&#xE6;n en m&#xE5;r]. 
De to &#xE6;delige blommer.

11.  Der blev stor gl&#xE6;de over al den g&#xE5;rd
&#x2014; Udi den hele sommer. &#x2014;
da bramsen f&#xE6;st sig fluen til brud. 
De to &#xE6;delige blommer.</danish_publication>
  <english_publication>The horsefly saddles his gray steed
-Trom tredeli, trom tradeli-
then he rides off to the fly&#x2019;s farm
-Trom tredeli, trom tradeli-

When he got to the fly&#x2019;s farm
the fly stood there combing its hair

&#x201C;And listen, fly, will you listen to me
and should you and I get married?&#x201D;

But the fly makes fun of the horsefly
[because she was much wealthier]

&#x201C;While I can sit on my mistress&#x2019;s platter,
you have to sit on the horse&#x2019;s behind

The horsefly took the fly by her wingbone
and he threw her down onto the cobblestone

That fly gets up and shakes herself off:
&#x201C;Oh, for shame&#x2019;s sake, you&#x2019;ve dirtied me!&#x201D;

[That fly she whimpered and she half cried]
&#x201C;So when should our wedding be?&#x201D;

--Yes, at the end of the summer and at the beginning of autumn,
that&#x2019;s when all the flies and horseflies are most plentiful&#x201D;

There was happiness, and it was big
-During the whole summer-
[That horsefly he got so fair a maiden-]

There was great happiness in the whole farm
-During the whole summer-
when the horsefly arranged to have the fly as his bride
-Those two noble plums
</english_publication>
